    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nThe context is using `Cython+coverage.py`. To reproduce the bug:\n \n* Build the package without tracing compiler directives/macros\n*  Build with `cythonize.compiler_directives` with `linetrace=True` +  `Extensions.define_macros` with tracing macros\n* The cache outputs a code not taking into account `linetrace`, but the macros are defined and passed on to the C/C++ compiler.\n* No trace is generated at runtime and the Cython code is not part of the coverage report\n\nI think the reason is because of the wrong assumption (`compiler_directives` does not influence code generation) that is written in a comment in `Compiler/Options.py:get_fingerprint`: \n\nThe fingerprinting function returns a string that will be fed to `hash.update` in `Build/Cache.py:transitive_fingerprint`\n\n``` python\ndef get_fingerprint(self):\n    data = {} \n    for key, value in self.__dict__.items():\n       if key in SOMEVALUES:\n           ... # many elif\n       elif key in ['compiler_directives']:\n           # directives passed on to the C compiler do not influence the generated code\n           continue\n       ... # many other elif\n\n    str_data = convert_to_string(data)\n    return data\n```\n\nBut that is wrong, as `Cython` with `linetrace=True` generates instrumentation code (such as in `Compiler/Code.py:write_trace_line()`).\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n_No response_\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nI would expect Cython cache fingerprinting to take into account `compiler_directives` (or at least partially `compiler_directive.linetrace`).\n\n### OS\n\nLinux (official docker image python:3.13-slim)\n\n### Python version\n\n3.13.12\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.2.4\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Thanks for the report. Yes, that looks like an incorrect assumption in the code. The `compiler_directives` instruct Cython itself to apply a certain behaviour, usually leading to different C code being generated. What might have been meant is the C macros etc., but the code is wrong as it stands.\n\nWe might want to be a bit selective about directives that do not impact the generated result but should otherwise include the directives state in the fingerprint.",
